{"id":"2111.11242","submitter":"Umair Shahzad","authors":"Umair Shahzad","title":"Prediction of Probabilistic Transient Stability Using Support Vector\n  Machine","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Transient stability assessment is an integral part of dynamic security\nassessment of power systems. Traditional methods of transient stability\nassessment, such as time domain simulation approach and direct methods, are\nappropriate for offline studies and thus, cannot be applied for online\ntransient stability prediction, which is a major requirement in modern power\nsystems. This motivated the requirement to apply an artificial\nintelligence-based approach. In this regard, supervised machine learning is\nbeneficial for predicting transient stability status, in the presence of\nuncertainties. Therefore, this paper examines the application of a binary\nsupport vector machine-based supervised machine learning, for predicting the\ntransient stability status of a power system, considering uncertainties of\nvarious factors, such as load, faulted line, fault type, fault location and\nfault clearing time. The support vector machine is trained using a Gaussian\nRadial Basis function kernel and its hyperparameters are optimized using\nBayesian optimization. Results obtained for the IEEE 14-bus test system\ndemonstrated that the proposed method offers a fast technique for probabilistic\ntransient stability status prediction, with an excellent accuracy. DIgSILENT\nPowerFactory and MATLAB was utilized for transient stability time-domain\nsimulations (for obtaining training data for support vector machine) and for\napplying support vector machine, respectively.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Nov 2021 14:46:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-23"}
